<font color="#FF0000">ARE YOU SURE, TOM?</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jun 26  1:33:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tom,<br><br>
&quot;The Viet Cong were South Vietnamese - not invaders from the North.  The(y) were widely supported in the Countryside.&quot;  Are you sure? Did you ask them?  Did you talk to them, not for more than just a few minutes, but gain their undivided trust?  How were you able to ascertain that the Viet Cong were &quot;widely suggorted in the countryside&quot;?  Was it because they agreed to fight us when a gun was held to their head?  <br><br>
Would you stand up and fight for South Vietnam as a South Vietnamese if you knew that the NVA assination teams were killing between 100 and 1000 local officials a month in South Vietnam in the early 1960's?  Or would you, like so many, stoically watch while our troops passed, knowing that if you were friendly toward them, you or your family might not be alive next month?<br><br>
You say that if the &quot;cause of the South Vietnamese government were just, it would have prevailed.&quot;  Would it? This seems a bit naive to me.<br><br>
It seems that battles, and wars, are not always determined by the &quot;justness&quot; of the cause.  Ghandi was the exception.  We have seen around the world that wars are won by the winner, the one who prevails.  We were unsuccessful in shutting off the ability of the North Vietnamese to fight through Cambodia and Laos, and undo our efforts easily when we were forced to leave.  We decided not to invade North Vietnam, even though the plans were in place.  As Mr. Guo above states, we did not have the political wherewithall to carry through and win.  We, in essence, had decided not to win.  As I stated in &quot;The Forum,&quot; once that was decided, the result was inevitable.  Too bad.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff') </code><p>


